text: Well at least this is better than the original trailer, which made him look like some ruthless psycho and Quinto look like the good guy, but here's one key problem.  Hitman is not an action game. It's a series based around finesse, stealth, getting in, hitting your target (and only your target if you can help it) and getting out as quickly, quietly, and efficiently as possible. It doesn't really lend itself to this festival of explosions and big shootouts.  It might be an okay action flick, but it's a poor Hitman adaptation.

text: I cant help but hate on this concept. I love the game, I really do, but this isn't Hitman 47. Any troll that disagrees has never embraced the essence of the game. 47 may have been the product of genetic engineering, but he was no super soldier. He's just one out of a dispensable clone army, an expendable asset with a psychological anomaly, the ability to question and reason. He has no amplified or enhanced physical attributes, in fact he is just as vulnerable as any individual save for his high tolerance for pain thanks to modified sensory endings. Like any soldier he had to be trained in the arts of war, weapon mastery, toxicology, espionage and counter intelligence, escape and evasion tactics, and of course shadow warfare. His methods have always been low tech, often exploiting the environment to set up the mark, sometimes procuring household items as improvised weapons. There was no question all his tactics required some degree of stealth, and his options were always one of two, death from a distance, or up close and personal. All that action packed mayhem we're seeing in this trailer is ridiculous. Might as well give him a costume and a shield.

This is most likely going to be despised if watched as a hitman movie. But if it's watched as something completely different and just a solo film it'll be better. text: Dear Hollywood producers, I will figure out to you what you all are missing with this mythical video game character and producing huge piles of bullcraps one after another.  1. Agent 47 is a legendary assassin. He plans his hits before and strikes from the shadow (or uses disguise). He never involves in a mass shootout in broad daylight. But you are making him a COD character in the movies. 2. He has no emotions or weaknesses for any particular gender or age. He does not give two shits about a 'damsel in distress'. 3. He is a cold blooded murderer. If situation demands then 47 will kill unhesitatingly an innocent eyewitness to protect his cover. 4. Somehow 47 is not an atheist. He has a strong belief over God. If you can imply this concept into the script successfully, then go for it. Otherwise don't bother about it. Its not mandatory. 5. 47 Never-Never-Ever falls in any kind of human relationship other than the mutual killing business contract.  Yes, he is that bad guy after whom John McClane or Bruce Wayne would go. He is the anti-hero. 47 is 'The Jackal'. Now make him like that. Believe me the movie will be a massive hit. We have enough 'Hero' stories. Now give us a proper Anti-hero. Thank you for reading my opinions patiently.

text: I haven't played the game and I can already tell this is going to be bloody shit. The "oh we're the same" shit is way too over done. I'd rather this story to focus on a mission not another sidekick training whatever. Maybe if this was like a sequel or something but they should really focus on just agent 47 himself. Like who gives a crap about him? Tell us the reason why we should give a shit by ONLY FOCUSING ON HIM HENSE THE TITLE.  The rope thing looks retarded. It somehow made me cringe. And based off of a scene where she's in a swimsuit and they focus on her body and whatever...love scene bound to happen. Agent 47 and sidekick become the bad ass couple yay! How about no write a better story... I'm a girl and tbh agent 47 is hot but that doesn't mean he has to have romance just because he's a hot assassin like what's your focus??? Oh wait I get it. Let's have some really good looking people fall in love in a crisis like in every other movie. No. Stop. Just stop. ROMANCE IS OK AS LONG AS ITS PORTRAYED TO FIT WITH A STORY. It's harder to focus on two genres and still like the movie. Mission impossible (can't remember which one) they portrayed the romance (even tho they just met and the relationship is purely physical) well where it doesn't mess with the story. I feel like it would in this story because we want to know who agent 47 is. Not about his relationships and how he can train a sidekick within 15 minutes of the movie. There is a whole list of things I hate about this and I just can't seem to comprehend. I'm not usually picky when it come to movies...but this....yeah this is bad. I know I sound like I've seen the movie but really everything in it just seems way too predictable. But is the video game any better? It Probably is.

Instead of exploring the deeply diverse and unique group of targets 47 has been presented with which has appeared in the series, they've yet again chosen to take the most fantastical aspects and make another action shlockfest.  47's targets were often terrible people, setting up heinous targets for him to knock out and exploring the shadowy agency would have been excellent in and of itself. text: This movie was almost really good as an adaptation. It definitely worked as an action movie, but that is the one issue I have with it. The Hitman games don‚Äôt really have much straight up action in them. You get rewarded for killing as few people as possible. You constantly need to change outfits, make things look like accidents, and almost everything takes a lot of time. They could have actually made a whole trilogy of movies, starting with a solid one that is more accurate, and with the good reception, people would be up for higher stakes and more action in the next. This one could have been a really good trilogy closer, because it is huge and action packed, and it doesn‚Äôt really warrant a sequel.
